Terraform - IAC

What is infrastructure as code ?      * constantly think about security and idompotency *

→ You manage and provision infrastructure using code or config 
→ You write script / configuration files that define your server , networks and resources 
→ Tools like terraform or Cloud Formation use that code to build or update your infrastructure 
→ Cloud agnostic and can be used with any cloud provider / Kubernetes service 

+ Infra as code - makes infra more repeatable , consistent and version controlled 

+ Cloud agnostic because terraform can download plugins so that it can deploy to  different providers 
- Providers = plugins 
- Terraform registry downloads the plugs 

+  User →   writes script / template / policy ( terraform , cloud formation etc) →  deploy →  AWS / Azure , Google 

+ the script / template / policy written can be Version controlled ( with GIT )

- Track changes , roll back to other versions , collaborate with team members 



What is Infrastructure Orchestration VS Config management ?

→ Infrastructure Orchestration - bring up infrastructure components like spinning up + connecting them ( orchestrating bigger picture ) 
- AWS CloudFormation 
- Terraform 

→ Configuration Management - infrastructure already exists and you need to keep that resource in the right state 
- Ansible 
- Chef 
- Puppet

Both work together as they orchestrate the environment & manage it’s configuration 



What is the Terraform workflow ?

1. You write Terraform configuration file    (/ INFRA definition )( in HCL ) - defining what resources and provide you want 
2. Terraform INIT → ensures necessary plugins are ready like AWS cloud 
3. Terraform PLAN → preview of your configuration file 
4. Terraform APPLY → applies preview change
5.  AWS cloud → creates , updates and versioning 


→ Terraform state file is created 
→ If you need to change - change config file 
→ Run terraform plan & terraform apply 
→ No longer need infra you run Terraform destroy



Terraform Tips ?

1. Testing and validation : Always verify configurations before deployment to avoid surprises 

2. Start with a minimum viable product (MVP) : Just enough infrastructure to function then expand from there 
- Iterate = make small improvements, testing along the way → no big suprises 

3. Implement DRY Software engineering principles: Reuse modules , variables and templates to keep IAC clean and maintainable 

4. Aws configure list-profiles - lists available profiles to be used
5.   cat ~/.aws/config  - specify in provider block region and profile wanted 




What is a Terraform state file ?

1 . State file is a up-to-date record of your current state of the infrastructure 
- Tracks the resources you created + their configurations 
- Mapping your code to your infrastructure 

This state file is essential so Terraform knows what exists so it can determine what to : Create , Update and destroy 
- Without this file Terraform can’t manage existing resources correctly 


2 . Terraform is designed to be IDEMPOTENT = so applying the configuration repeatedly doesn’t change anything unless your current state and  desired state is different 

- Specific change in config = particular change , not a whole update 



What is the current state VS  Desired state in Terraform ?

Current state = State file -> the record of the current state of your infrastructure ( .tfstate )

Desired state = the changes you want to have like adding 2 EC2 instances ( .tf )

Desired state is written in your Terraform configuration 

So Terraform compares the 2 and changes state file accordingly ( .tf VS .tfstate )



Deploying infrastructure with terraform questions to think about *

How is infrastructure deployed via terraform ?

How are the connections to cloud established in order for your deployments to reach the cloud ?

How do I deploy things safely and not break anything ?



What are Terraform providers and how to establish connection ?

Terraform provider = a plugin that allows you to interact with cloud platforms , services so Terraform can manage resources in the cloud 

This is part of the configuration file for our desired state .tf 

Terraform {
required_providers                    [ where to get the provider plugin section ]
aws = {                                        the provider your configuration needs  
source = "hashicorp/aws"         where Terraform downloads provider ( i.e hashicorp registry )
version = "5.62.0"                      locks version for consistency 
        }
    } }

Provider "aws" {                         Tells Terraform which services to interact with and the resources down below [ section ]
#Configuration options
}

WORFLOW 

What does Terraform INIT do ?

INIT - initialises ( sets up ) your working directory for Terraform 

→ configures the backend - where Terraform will store the  .tfstate file , whether that’s local file on computer or remotely ( like in S3 ) = now allows Idompotency 
→ It downloads your provider plugins ( source and version )
→ Initialises Modules - if using modules ( reusable pieces of configuration ) , it downloads them too 
→ prepares working directory it gets everything ready so you can plan or apply changes after 


What does Terraform PLAN do ? 

PLAN - doesn’t change anything and is just a preview 

+ create = Resources are created 
~ update in place = Resources are updated / modified 

– destroy = Resources that will be deleted 
￼

→ it compares your current state .tfstate to your configuration ( desired state ) .tf
→ it shows what will be created , update or destroyed 
→ review changes before applying them 
→ helps catch errors before infra changes made 


What does Terraform APPLY do ? 

Apply - Takes the plan and executes planned changes 

→ It creates , updates and destroys real infrastructure to match your configuration 
→ you can review and confirm before you proceed 
→ after APPLY the infrastructure state matches your desired state 
→ state file .tfstate is then updated to reflect the current changed infrastructure 
￼

What does Terraform DESTROY do ? 

Destroy  → removes the infrastructure that the state file says been created and cleans up 

→  Deletes all infrastructure created 
→ reads state file .tfstate to know what resources to remove 
→ shows you a plan of what will be destroyed 
→  you confirm and state file now reflects the resources are gone 


Reading and configuring a Resource block in Terraform ? 

Resource "aws_instance" "Test" {                  Resource type , “local name of the insurance ”
ami = "ami-01572eda7c4411960"                   amazon machine image = template of your Virtual machine (ec2) will be used to launch the image 
instance_type = "t2.micro"                              defines the size and capacity (hardware configuration like cpu and memory )
Tags = {
Name = "Helloworld"                                        Tags to help identify resource in the AWS console ( might say DEV , PROD , STAGING)( Best practice )


Terraform importing resources from the cloud ?

The ‘terraform import’ command allows you to import existing resources that weren’t built on Terraform to be under the management of terraform 

→ You want to integrate Terraform into your existing infrastructure without recreating from scratch 
→ Identify the resource you want to import 
→ use import block to import instances using the id 
→  Create the resource block in terraform config  = provider , region , resource “x” and “name”
→ now you have it under terraform management 

￼

→ terraform import aws_instance.web I-12345678
=  run a terraform plan and keep making changes until your desired state matches your current state .tfstate 
- You want to obtain a 0 changes when your terraform planning and applying 


Practically 

Add another resource block with ami , instance type , subnet id + tag name 
Then terraform plan your way to zero changes 




Local state files and Remote statefiles

Local state file = working alone , personal project and one person controlling infrastructure 

Remote state file = stores state file remotely in AWS S3 / Terraform cloud - suitable for team collaboration 
- Centralises the state so team can collaborate 
- Ensures consistency 
- When using S3 with dynamoDB / terraform cloud for locking - ensures one person at a time can change state file .tfstate 
- S3 stores the .tfstate and dynamoDB state locks and provides versioning and lock history 
- Commonly used with a remote backend like S3 , Terraform cloud / remote database in terraform provider block 

Production issues : 
→ without state locking there can be infrastructure drift (real world infra and configuration not matching)
→ data corruption or loss / not backed up 
→ website / app downtime 

Best practices:
→ make sure to constantly backup 
→ make sure your backend supports state locking 
→ encrypt data and apply access controls 
→ don’t commit state files to GitHub but might need versioning from git

Add remote s3 backend to terraform block with : 

terraform {
  backend "s3" {
    bucket = "mybucket"
    key    = "path/to/my/key"
    region = "us-east-1"
  }
}


Entire Terraform work flow ?

Terraform init - initialises , creates working directory for config files (download providers etc )and remote backend for state file 
Terraform validate - helps with syntax errors and if config files structures well 
Terraform plan - comparing desired .tf with state file .tfstate and showing differences 
Terraform apply - apply changes from desired to state file and updating state file after
Terraform destroy - managed way to tear down terraform managed infrastructure 


Why are Terraform Variables used?

Variables are used to make your code more flexible and to avoid sifting through terraform documentation 
- They have reusable configuration instead of hard coding values in your .tf config files 
- This makes it adaptable across dev , staging , production 
- Dynamic configuration without altering code 
- Reducing redundancy & potential errors 
- Manage different environments with the same configurations 
- Define values once and modules for reusable code 

Main .tf = for resources 
Variables.tf = to hold your resource block definitions and how to use them 
Outputs.tf = if you want to expose data 
Providers.tf

module ( call upon in Root configuration ) = premade resource block , used multiple times and you can define values 


Input variables Vs Local variables in Terraform ? 

Input variables are values you supply externally like what the instance type Is  = t2.micro

Local variables are shortcuts/ code blocks you use when you want to repeatable use code without repeating yourself
- You use local variables to Keep code dry 
- Avoiding repeating yourself 
- Help reduce redundancy 

→ you can put them in your main tf or you can assign them to their own locals.tf (safe to commit)
￼

Output variables exposes data that is critical to see in terminal for things like automation , manual intervention or changing terraform configs 
- Be cautious using using sensitive information 
- And use value= “sensitive” in order to hide critical things 
